{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b59e56eba5bf4d80", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tTraceback Translators Against Forgetting in\n2\tContinual Fake Speech Detection\n3\tEnrico Gottardis\n4\t\n5\tMattia Tamiazzo\n6\t\n7\tSimone Milani\n8\t\n9\tarXiv:2607.12569v1 [cs.CV] 14 Jul 2026\n10\t\n11\tDepartment of Information Engineering Department of Information Engineering Department of Information Engineering\n12\tUniversity of Padova\n13\tUniversity of Padova\n14\tUniversity of Padova\n15\tPadova, Italy\n16\tPadova, Italy\n17\tPadova, Italy\n18\tsimone.milani@dei.unipd.it\n19\tmattia.tamiazzo.1@phd.unipd.it\n20\tenrico.gottardis@studenti.unipd.it\n21\t\n22\tAbstract—Fake speech detectors are increasingly challenged by\n23\tthe development of new and more accurate generative models. To\n24\tcope with this problem, continual learning techniques are nowadays widely considered feasible strategies for updating models\n25\tto new datasets, but they also lead to decreased performance on\n26\tpreviously seen samples (catastrophic forgetting). In this work,\n27\twe propose a forgetting-resilient solution based on the adoption\n28\tof domain translators within a frozen detector, which remaps the\n29\tnew feature spaces into the original ones by means of a traceback\n30\ttranslator network. Experimental results show that this strategy\n31\tenables the achievement of high detection rates with respect to\n32\ttraditional retraining, while minimizing the computational effort\n33\tand preserving the detection accuracy on previous data.\n34\tIndex Terms—audio forensics, deepfake, continual learning,\n35\tdomain adaptation, catastrophic forgetting\n36\t\n37\tI. I NTRODUCTION AND RELATED WORKS\n38\tIn recent years, the widespread adoption and development\n39\tof synthetic speech generators [1] have forced researchers and\n40\tcybersecurity experts to create new deepfake detectors [2].\n41\tAs a matter of fact, existing detectors need to be updated\n42\tthrough continual retraining in which old datasets are integrated with new samples, but unfortunately the access to the\n43\toriginal data is not always guaranteed. A possible alternative\n44\tconsists in fine-tuning pre-trained models on the sole novel\n45\tdataset, but this leads to undesired learning drifts, such as\n46\tcatastrophic forgetting, where knowledge learned from old\n47\tsamples is diluted by new data.\n48\tTo address such issues, transfer learning, domain adaptation\n49\tand continual learning techniques have been recently investigated in the literature [3]–[10]. Methods based on transfer\n50\tlearning and domain adaptation aim at adapting pre-trained\n51\tmodels and transferring knowledge across domains. These\n52\tapproaches include fine-tuning using Low-Rank Adaptation\n53\t[3], cross-lingual knowledge transfer [4], and unsupervised\n54\tdomain adaptation to handle distribution shifts [5]. Strategies\n55\tThis work was funded by the European Union under the Italian National\n56\tRecovery and Resilience Plan (NRRP) of NextGenerationEU, with a partnership on “Telecommunications of the Future” (PE00000001 - program\n57\t“RESTART”). We thank the partnership and collaboration with the São Paulo\n58\tResearch Foundation (Fapesp) Horus project, Grant #2023/12865-8. This\n59\tmanuscript reflects only the authors’ views and opinions, neither EU nor the\n60\tEuropean Commission nor FAPESP can be considered responsible for them.\n61\tAll of the authors have revised the document and confirm the findings.\n62\t\n63\tbased on continual learning employ memory-based and regularization methods, such as self-adaptive learning to modify\n64\tthe gradient direction and retain previously learned knowledge\n65\t[6], and model distillation techniques [7], [8]. The authors\n66\tof [9] propose a continual learning method to incrementally\n67\ttrain fake audio detectors on new spoofing attacks. The\n68\tmodel includes a knowledge distillation loss and a similarity\n69\tconstraint that aligns genuine sample representations across\n70\tdifferent domains, improving detection performance.\n71\tTo improve generalization across unseen data, a Mixture of\n72\tExperts architecture is proposed in [10]. Multiple specialized\n73\texperts are trained on specific datasets, and their predictions\n74\tare combined through a gating mechanism. By distributing\n75\tspecialized knowledge across multiple modules, the architecture is able to outperform single-model baselines in a crossdataset scenario.\n76\tThe study in [11] investigates the effectiveness of continual\n77\tlearning by comparing different retraining strategies. The\n78\tdetector is divided into two logical sections (encoder and\n79\tclassification modules), and experiments evaluate the classification performance by applying a continual learning approach\n80\t[9] to the entire model, or selectively to one section while\n81\tfreezing the other. Experimental results show that retraining\n82\tthe encoder while freezing the classifier offers a better balance between learning novel data and maintaining previously\n83\tacquired knowledge.\n84\tIn this paper, we introduce a lightweight traceback domain\n85\ttranslator into a frozen classifier in order to adapt it to\n86\tnew deepfake generators and sampling setups and mitigate\n87\tcatastrophic forgetting. It is possible to summarize the main\n88\tcontributions as follows:\n89\tWe propose a new continual learning approach for synthetic speech detection, where traditional fine-tuning is\n90\treplaced by the introduction of a lightweight domain\n91\ttranslator within a frozen classifier.\n92\t• The translator-based approach is compared to other\n93\tdomain-adaptation solutions; the number of retrained\n94\tparameters is minimized while maximizing accuracies on\n95\tboth new and old datasets.\n96\t• The proposed solution was tested in a multilingual setup\n97\t(including both English and Chinese sentences), showing\n98\t•\n99\t\n100\t\fOutput\n101\tn classes\n102\t\n103\tLinear 128→7\n104\t\n105\tLinear 512→128\n106\tBN+ReLU\n107\tDropout\n108\t\n109\tGlobal Avg Pool\n110\t\n111\tLayer4\n112\t512-ch, 4×4\n113\t\n114\tLayer3\n115\t256-ch, 8×8\n116\t\n117\tLayer2\n118\t128-ch, 16×16\n119\t\n120\tLayer1\n121\t64-ch, 32×32\n122\t\n123\tConv1\n124\t7×7, 64\n125\tBN+ReLU\n126\tMax Pool\n127\t\n128\tInput\n129\t128×128\n130\t\n131\tFig. 1. Architecture of the customized ResNet18 used in the work.\n132\t\n133\twhere w = [6, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1] ∈ RK is the vector of weights,\n134\twith wc the c-th element of w, ϵ = 0.08, K = 7 represents the\n135\tnumber of classes, and N is the batch size. From experimental\n136\tresults, we noticed a tendency of the model to misclassify real\n137\tsamples as if they were synthetic from class 6. For this reason,\n138\twe added an extra penalty defined as:\n139\tLpenalty = λ\n140\t\n141\tN\n142\tX\n143\t\n144\t\u0001\n145\t1 yi = 0 ∧ arg max p̂i,c = 6 ,\n146\t\n147\ti=1\n148\t\n149\tc\n150\t\n151\tthat the proposed approach can also be used for a crosslingual adaptation.\n152\t• Performance was further improved by means of generative data augmentation based on diffusion models.\n153\t\n154\twith λ = 5.0, leading to a combined classifier loss:\n155\t\n156\tII. C ONTINUAL LEARNING AND CATASTROPHIC\n157\tFORGETTING IN SYNTHETIC SPEECH DETECTION MODELS\n158\t\n159\tC. Continual Learning Strategies\n160\t\n161\tIn order to tackle the problem of forgetting in continual\n162\tlearning for synthetic audio classification, we tested different\n163\tadaptation methods measuring their impacts on a simple but\n164\teffective classifier.\n165\tA. Dataset pre-processing\n166\tThe adopted architecture processes the input signal and\n167\tgenerates sets of MFCC spectrograms including 128-frequency\n168\tcoefficients and spanning a time window of 42 frames around\n169\tsalient instants (leading to 128 × 42 matrices). Salient instants\n170\tare selected at points where the signal evolves from a silenced\n171\tinterval to a voiced one since their relevance has already been\n172\thighlighted in some previous works [12], [13].\n173\tAlthough multiple spectrograms can be extracted from a\n174\tsingle file, for some classes the number of available samples\n175\twas limited, leading to a high class imbalance between real\n176\tand synthetic audio samples. To address this issue, we resorted\n177\tto a dataset generative process based on a diffusion model\n178\timplemented in [14]. Specifically, we employed a 2D UNet architecture [15] as the core denoising component of\n179\tthe diffusion process, enabling the generation of synthetic\n180\tspectrogram samples while preserving the spatial structure and\n181\tdimensions of the input representations. To further compensate\n182\tfor the class imbalance, classic data augmentation was used,\n183\tand an imbalanced sampler was adopted.\n184\tB. Audio deepfake detection\n185\tThe classification model is based on a customized ResNet18\n186\t[16] (see Fig. 1), where the first convolutional layer is frozen\n187\tand the classifier head consists of two fully-connected layers\n188\twith normalization and dropout.\n189\tThe model was trained using a weighted custom CrossEntropy loss with label smoothing, to reduce over-confidence:\n190\tN K−1\n191\t\n192\t1 XX\n193\twc ỹi,c log p̂i,c ,\n194\tN i=1 c=0\n195\t(\n196\t1 − ϵ, c = yi\n197\tỹi,c =\n198\tϵ/K, c ̸= yi\n199\t\n200\tLCE = −\n201\t\n202\t(1)\n203\t\n204\tLclassifier = LCE + Lpenalty .\n205\t\n206\t(2)\n207\t\n208\t(3)\n209\t\n210\tFor validation, we employed a standard Cross-Entropy loss.\n211\t\n212\tAfter obtaining a solid backbone model to perform detection\n213\ton audio deepfakes, we analyzed different approaches to\n214\tperform continual learning on other datasets.\n215\t1) Full retraining: The first approach was to retrain the\n216\twhole network on the new dataset. This common method\n217\tis largely implemented by other researchers [11], leading to\n218\timpressive performance. However, the main drawback is the\n219\tcatastrophic forgetting phenomenon: the model learns the new\n220\trepresentation of data, forgetting the previous task.\n221\t2) Domain adaptation: In order to reduce the catastrophic\n222\tforgetting issue, we opted to retrain only part of the whole\n223\tarchitecture. In particular, we considered adopting a domain\n224\tadaptation approach by selectively retraining only the Batch\n225\tNormalization (BN) layers, while keeping the rest of the model\n226\tfrozen (sometimes called Continual Normalization [17]). This\n227\tmethod has two main advantages: the retraining of the model\n228\trequires only the new dataset, on which the network will be\n229\tfine-tuned, and the training will be faster, as the only learnable\n230\tparameters are the BN layers.\n231\t3) Domain Translation: This idea consists of shifting the\n232\tdistributions of real and fake samples in the target domain to\n233\tmake them similar to those in the source domain.\n234\tAlthough the proposed translator shares similarities with\n235\tadapter modules explored in [18]–[20], its role and characteristics are different. The translator is applied after the embedding\n236\tlayer and is trained to perform class-conditional alignment of\n237\treal or fake feature distributions across domains. By freezing\n238\tthe backbone and adapting only this lightweight module, the\n239\tapproach limits catastrophic forgetting. To the best of our\n240\tknowledge, the use of simple adapter-like architectures has not\n241\tbeen previously explored for distribution alignment in audio\n242\tdeepfake detection.\n243\tWe considered the features created from the model after\n244\tthe embedding, which provides vectors in a 128-dimensional\n245\tlatent space. Before providing these vectors to the fully\n246\tconnected part of the model, we processed them with the\n247\tarchitecture described in Fig. 2, where a fully-connected\n248\tmodel with a bottleneck db = 32 is followed by a residual\n249\tconnection y = x + f (LN(x)), shown in the picture with a\n250\tdashed line. To promote the translation process, the training\n251\t\n252\t\fTABLE I\n253\tM ODEL COMPARISON FOR CLASSIFICATION TASK ON ASV SPOOF 2019.\n254\tArchitecture\n255\tCustom ResNet18\n256\tAST [30]\n257\tConvNeXT-Tiny [29]\n258\tResNet18 - multiclass [16]\n259\tResNet18 - binary [16]\n260\tEfficientNet B0 [27]\n261\tEfficientNet B1 [27]\n262\tMobileNet V3 Large [28]\n263\t\n264\tFig. 2. Block diagram for the translator model.\n265\t\n266\tloss consists of three elements: the classifier loss described\n267\tin (3), the CORrelation ALignment (CORAL) loss [21] and\n268\tPrototype Consistency (PC) [22] loss. While the CORAL\n269\tloss aims at minimizing the mean and variance between real\n270\tand fake samples from the source and the target datasets,\n271\tPC minimizes the intra-class distance. Given source features\n272\tzs ∈ RNB ×128 with labels ys ∈ {0, . . . , 6} and target\n273\tfeatures zt ∈ RNB ×128 with labels yt ∈ {0, 1}, with NB\n274\tbeing the batch size, we define their batch-wise means µreal\n275\ts ,\n276\tfake\n277\tfake\n278\tas class prototypes and the corresponding\n279\tµreal\n280\tt , µs , µt\n281\tcovariance matrices\n282\tas Σs and Σt . Let us define\n283\t\u0010\n284\t\u0011 the norm\n285\treal 2\n286\tfake\n287\t2\n288\t∥µs − µt ∥22 = ∥µreal\n289\t− µfake\n290\ts − µt ∥2 + ∥µs\n291\tt ∥2 .\n292\tThe prototype consistency loss is defined as:\n293\t1\n294\t(4)\n295\tLPC = ∥µs − µt ∥22 .\n296\t2\n297\tDenoting ∥·∥2F as the squared matrix Frobenius norm, it is\n298\tthen possible to compute the CORAL loss as:\n299\tLCORAL = ∥µs − µt ∥22 +\n300\t|\n301\t\n302\t{z\n303\t\n304\t}\n305\t\n306\tmean alignment\n307\t\n308\t∥Σs − Σt ∥2F\n309\t|\n310\t\n311\t{z\n312\t\n313\t.\n314\t\n315\t(5)\n316\t\n317\t}\n318\t\n319\tcovariance alignment\n320\t\n321\tThe final training loss is defined as:\n322\tLtotal = Lclassifier + λCORAL LCORAL + λP C LPC\n323\t\n324\t(6)\n325\t\n326\twhere λCORAL and λP C are two regularization terms, experimentally set to 0.05 and 0.01 respectively.\n327\tIII. E XPERIMENTAL SETUP\n328\tThe experimental setting for our continual learning approach was defined based on several state-of-the-art corpora\n329\tof samples.\n330\tASVspoof 2019 (ASV19) [23]. The dataset was introduced to\n331\tassess countermeasures against synthetic and voice-converted\n332\tspeech in English and is organized into three subsets: train,\n333\tdevelopment, and evaluation. It is one of the most widely used\n334\tbenchmark datasets for audio deepfake detection.\n335\tFakeOrReal (FoR) [24]. The dataset contains English bona\n336\tfide and synthetic speech generated by various Text-To-Speech\n337\t(TTS) systems, including both open-source and commercial\n338\ttools. The real speech content is sourced from publicly available speech datasets.\n339\tIn-The-Wild (ITW) [25]. This corpus aims to assess speech\n340\tdetectors in a real-world scenario and includes real and synthetic audio samples collected from English-speaking celebrities and politicians. Covering diverse recording conditions and\n341\t\n342\tDev. accuracy\n343\t\n344\tDev. loss\n345\t\n346\tTr. epochs\n347\t\n348\t0.994\n349\t0.994\n350\t0.904\n351\t0.883\n352\t0.860\n353\t0.823\n354\t0.776\n355\t0.753\n356\t\n357\t0.112\n358\t0.193\n359\t0.329\n360\t0.269\n361\t0.398\n362\t0.461\n363\t0.536\n364\t0.588\n365\t\n366\t240\n367\t324\n368\t296\n369\t148\n370\t110\n371\t60\n372\t30\n373\t100\n374\t\n375\tgenerative methods, it is particularly useful for evaluating\n376\tmodel robustness.\n377\tADD 2022 (ADD22) [26]. The dataset includes genuine and\n378\tsynthetic Mandarin Chinese audio samples. It is designed to\n379\tevaluate deepfake detection systems across various conditions,\n380\tsuch as low-quality and partially fake audio tracks.\n381\tThe dataset used to train the baseline model is the training\n382\tsubset of ASVspoof 2019. Although training was performed\n383\ton individual spectrograms, inference results were aggregated\n384\tat the audio-excerpt level using majority voting over multiple\n385\tspectrograms extracted from the same sample.\n386\tIV. R ESULTS\n387\tThis section presents a preliminary backbone selection\n388\tstudy, followed by the evaluation of the proposed continual\n389\tlearning strategies, and an ablation analysis.\n390\tA. Backbone Architecture Selection\n391\tBefore evaluating the proposed continual learning strategies, we performed a preliminary study to identify a suitable\n392\tbackbone model for the detection task. Several architectures\n393\twere considered, evaluating them on the ASVspoof 2019\n394\tdevelopment set.\n395\tTable I reports the comparison among the investigated\n396\tarchitectures. Among the evaluated models, the customized\n397\tResNet18 provided the best performance even compared\n398\tto more complex architectures, like EfficientNet [27], MobileNet [28], and ConvNeXT-Tiny [29]. The Audio Spectrogram Transformer (AST) [30] achieved comparable accuracy; however, it requires substantially higher computational\n399\tresources, with approximately 86 million trainable parameters\n400\tcompared to the 11 million parameters of ResNet18, as well\n401\tas longer training times.\n402\tB. Main Experimental Results\n403\tThe results obtained on the evaluation datasets are summarized in Table II. The baseline model achieves performance comparable to that reported in [11], evaluated using\n404\tthe Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve, and the\n405\tEqual Error Rate (EER). Performance is also quantified using\n406\tthe Area Under the Curve (AUC). The results of the three\n407\tcontinual learning strategies introduced in II-C are illustrated\n408\tin Fig.3. It can be observed that full retraining performs very\n409\twell on the target dataset (average 1.44% EER on new dataset),\n410\tbut results in a dramatic loss of accuracy on the source dataset\n411\t\n412\t\fTABLE II\n413\tE XPERIMENTAL RESULTS OF THE PROPOSED METHODS . R ESULTS IN BRACKETS ARE REFERRED TO THE PERFORMANCE ON THE ASV SPOOF 2019\n414\tEVALUATION SET AFTER SPECIALIZATION ( RETRAINING ). T HE METHOD IS COMPARED WITH THE LCNN- BASED MODEL IN [11].\n415\tASV19\n416\t\n417\tMethod\n418\t\n419\tFOR\n420\t\n421\tITW\n422\t\n423\tADD22\n424\t\n425\tAUC (%)\n426\t\n427\tEER (%)\n428\t\n429\tAUC (%)\n430\t\n431\tEER (%)\n432\t\n433\tAUC (%)\n434\t\n435\tEER (%)\n436\t\n437\tAUC (%)\n438\t\n439\tEER (%)\n440\t\n441\tBaseline model\n442\tFull retraining\n443\tDomain adaptation\n444\tDomain translation\n445\t\n446\t95.0\n447\t–\n448\t–\n449\t–\n450\t\n451\t9.74\n452\t–\n453\t–\n454\t–\n455\t\n456\t49.8\n457\t99.7 (61.2)\n458\t97.4 (63.1)\n459\t96.0 (95.0)\n460\t\n461\t50.2\n462\t3.27 (43.2)\n463\t8.26 (40.7)\n464\t11.37 (9.74)\n465\t\n466\t49.6\n467\t100 (59.6)\n468\t96.3 (77.6)\n469\t95.4 (95.0)\n470\t\n471\t50.3\n472\t0.28 (43.8)\n473\t9.15 (28.8)\n474\t10.64 (9.74)\n475\t\n476\t30.8\n477\t100 (22.1)\n478\t99.3 (46.0)\n479\t98.1 (95.0)\n480\t\n481\t62.9\n482\t0.78 (71.8)\n483\t4.02 (52.2)\n484\t6.96 (9.74)\n485\t\n486\tCL ALL [11]\n487\tCL Mc [11]\n488\tCL Me [11]\n489\t\n490\t95.7\n491\t–\n492\t–\n493\t\n494\t11.1\n495\t–\n496\t–\n497\t\n498\t99.0 (94.0)\n499\t98.8 (93.2)\n500\t98.9 (93.2)\n501\t\n502\t4.20 (13.6)\n503\t5.00 (14.0)\n504\t4.90 (13.4)\n505\t\n506\t99.8 (92.1)\n507\t99.5 (93.1)\n508\t99.0 (91.8)\n509\t\n510\t1.60 (15.4)\n511\t2.80 (14.6)\n512\t4.10 (15.1)\n513\t\n514\t–\n515\t–\n516\t–\n517\t\n518\t–\n519\t–\n520\t–\n521\t\n522\t(a) ROC plots for the full retraining of\n523\tthe model.\n524\t\n525\t(b) ROC plots for the domain adaptation approach.\n526\t\n527\t(c) ROC plots for the domain translation approach.\n528\t\n529\tFig. 3. Comparison of the ROC plots obtained testing the proposed methods.\n530\t\n531\tTABLE III\n532\tN UMBER OF PARAMETERS OF OUR METHODS COMPARED WITH THE\n533\tLCNN MODEL EMPLOYED IN [11].\n534\tMethod\n535\t\n536\t# Trained parameters\n537\t\n538\tFull retraining\n539\tDomain adaptation\n540\tDomain translation\n541\t\n542\t11095K\n543\t10K\n544\t21K\n545\t\n546\tCL ALL [11]\n547\tCL Mc [11]\n548\tCL Me [11]\n549\t\n550\t5556K\n551\t521K\n552\t5035K\n553\t\n554\tASVspoof 2019 (−52% AUC and +52.9% EER on average).\n555\tThe largest loss is reasonably observed on ADD since the\n556\tlanguage change from English to Chinese. Performing a partial\n557\tupdate (domain adaptation) proved to be more robust, as\n558\tthe average AUC decrease is 2.3% on the target domain,\n559\tbut the loss on the source domain is 38% AUC and EER\n560\tincreases by 30.8% on average. It is also worth noting that\n561\tonly a small number of parameters must be retrained (see\n562\tTable III), making it very efficient. The domain translation\n563\tstrategy represents a good trade-off between classification\n564\tperformances and computational complexity since the average\n565\tAUC loss on target domains is 3.4%, but we preserve the\n566\taccuracy on the source domain (95.4% AUC, 9.74% EER)\n567\twhile updating only a limited number of parameters.\n568\tThe experimental results also show that the proposed approaches can be applied to cross-lingual adaptation, since\n569\t\n570\tADD dataset includes Chinese language speech samples. The\n571\ttraceback translation model proves to be capable of handling\n572\tdatasets in different languages while keeping the same classification accuracy.\n573\tC. Ablation studies\n574\tTo determine the impact of diffusion-based data augmentation on model performance, we trained the baseline model on\n575\tonly the ASVspoof 2019 training set, and then we included\n576\tboth original and generated samples. Experimental results\n577\tshow consistent performance gains with data augmentation:\n578\tclassification accuracy increased from 81.9% to 83.7%, while\n579\tthe AUC improved from 91.5% to 95.0%.\n580\tMoreover, we enabled/disabled the different components\n581\tin (6) and evaluated their impact on the final accuracy. With\n582\tonly LPC (Prototype-Consistency), EER for FoR/ITW/ADD\n583\tincreases to 10.75%, 11.87%, 7.34% respectively, while using\n584\tLCORAL only (CORAL loss), the respective EER is 11.84%,\n585\t9.05%, 7.72%, showing that their combination is, on average,\n586\tmore effective on all the datasets.\n587\tV. C ONCLUSIONS\n588\tIn this paper, we investigated the effectiveness of multiple\n589\tcontinual learning techniques for audio deepfake detection to\n590\tmitigate the problem of catastrophic forgetting.\n591\tOur experiments showed that all the approaches achieve\n592\tgood detection performance, but the full retraining and domain\n593\t\n594\t\fadaptation methods are not able to retain previously learned\n595\tknowledge. We proposed a novel approach based on domain\n596\ttranslation that achieves high detection rates without requiring\n597\tthe retraining of the backbone architecture and, at the same\n598\ttime, preserves the detection accuracy on the original dataset.\n599\tFuture work will focus on extending the evaluation to a\n600\tlarger number of datasets to test scalability and robustness\n601\tagainst different types of domain shifts. Additionally, exploring different model architectures could further improve\n602\tperformance in cross-domain and cross-lingual audio deepfake\n603\tdetection.\n604\tACKNOWLEDGMENT\n605\tThe authors would like to thank Davide Salvi, Viola Negroni, Luca Bondi, Paolo Bestagini, and Stefano Tubaro of\n606\tPolitecnico di Milano for their support in the experimental\n607\tcomparison with [11].\n608\tR EFERENCES\n609\t[1] K. Bhagtani, A. K. S. Yadav, P. Bestagini, and E. J. Delp, “Are\n610\trecent deepfake speech generators detectable?” in Proceedings of\n611\tthe 2024 ACM Workshop on Information Hiding and Multimedia\n612\tSecurity, ser. IH&MMSec ’24. New York, NY, USA: Association\n613\tfor Computing Machinery, 2024, p. 277–282. [Online]. Available:\n614\thttps://doi.org/10.1145/3658664.3659658\n